Determination of second-order rate constant (k
ACMP,OH
) for the reaction of ACMP and OH by competition kinetics. A) Relative concentrations of ACMP and pCBA as a function of the ozone dose. B) Natural logarithm of ACMP relative concentration vs natural logarithm of pCBA relative concentration. Conditions: [ACMP]0 =[pCBA]0 =4μM, pH7, temperature=20±2°C.

ce:section.ce:para:
By plotting the natural logarithm of the relative residual concentration of ACMP against the ozone exposure, ∫[O
3
]dt, a linear relation was obtained. The slope of the function corresponds to the second-order kinetic constant for the reaction between ACMP and molecular ozone. Fig. 1 shows the relative concentration of ACMP and ozone during the experiment (A), as well as the logarithmic relative concentration of ACMP as a function of ∫[O
3
]dt (B). The ozone exposure was determined by calculating the area under the ozone decay curve, employing the trapezoidal method of numerical integration. k
ACMP-O3 was determined to be 0.25±0.02M−1 s−1.
